(6, '<h1 id=\"firstHeading\" class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\" style=\"text-align: center; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background: none; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0.25em; margin-left: 0px; overflow: visible; padding: 0px; border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177); font-size: 1.8em; line-height: 1.3; font-family: &quot;Linux Libertine&quot;, Georgia, Times, serif;\"><b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;;\">WYSIWYG</span></b></h1><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Before the adoption of WYSIWYG techniques, text appeared in editors using the system standard&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typeface\" title=\"Typeface\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">typeface</a>&nbsp;and style with little indication of layout (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margin_(typography)\" title=\"Margin (typography)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">margins</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line-spacing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Line-spacing\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">spacing</a>, etc.). Users were required to enter special non-printing&nbsp;<i>control codes</i>&nbsp;(now referred to as markup&nbsp;<i>code tags</i>) to indicate that some text should be in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boldface\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Boldface\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">boldface</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italic_type\" title=\"Italic type\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">italics</a>, or a different&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typeface\" title=\"Typeface\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">typeface</a>&nbsp;or size. In this environment there was very little distinction between&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text_editor\" title=\"Text editor\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">text editors</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word_processor\" title=\"Word processor\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">word processors</a>.</p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">These applications typically used an arbitrary&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language\" title=\"Markup language\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">markup language</a>&nbsp;to define the codes/tags. Each program had its own special way to format a document, and it was a difficult and time-consuming process to change from one word processor to another.</p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The use of markup tags and codes remains popular today in some applications due to their ability to store complex formatting information. When the tags are made visible in the editor, however, they occupy space in the unformatted text, and as a result can disrupt the desired layout and flow.</p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bravo_(software)\" title=\"Bravo (software)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Bravo</a>, a document preparation program for the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alto_(computer)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Alto (computer)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Alto</a>&nbsp;produced at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PARC_(company)\" title=\"PARC (company)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Xerox PARC</a>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butler_Lampson\" title=\"Butler Lampson\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Butler Lampson</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Simonyi\" title=\"Charles Simonyi\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Charles Simonyi</a>&nbsp;and colleagues in 1974, is generally considered to be the first program to incorporate the WYSIWYG technology,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG#cite_note-6\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[6]</a></sup>&nbsp;displaying text with formatting (e.g. with justification, fonts, and proportional spacing of characters).<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG#cite_note-7\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[7]</a></sup>&nbsp;The Alto monitor (72&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixels_per_inch\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pixels per inch\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">PPI</a>, based on the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(typography)\" title=\"Point (typography)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">typographic unit</a>) was designed so that one full page of text could be seen and then printed on the first&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laser_printer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Laser printer\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">laser printers</a>. When the text was laid out on the screen, 72 PPI font metric files were used, but when printed, 300 PPI files were used. As a result, one would occasionally find characters and words that are slightly off—a problem that would continue up to this day.</p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Bravo was released commercially, and the software eventually included in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xerox_Star\" title=\"Xerox Star\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Xerox Star</a>&nbsp;can be seen as a direct descendant of it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG#cite_note-8\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[8]</a></sup></p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">In late 1978, in parallel with but independent of the work at Xerox PARC,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hewlett_Packard\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hewlett Packard\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Hewlett Packard</a>&nbsp;developed and released the first commercial WYSIWYG software application for producing overhead slides (or what today are referred to as presentation graphics). The first release, named&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BRUNO\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BRUNO\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">BRUNO</a>&nbsp;(after an HP sales training puppet), ran on the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP_1000\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"HP 1000\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">HP 1000</a>&nbsp;minicomputer, taking advantage of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP_2640\" title=\"HP 2640\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">HP 2640</a>—HP\'s first bitmapped computer terminal.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BRUNO\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BRUNO\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">BRUNO</a>&nbsp;was then ported to the HP-3000 and re-released as \"HP Draw\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG#cite_note-9\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[9]</a></sup></p><p style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><br></sup></p><p style=\"text-align: center; margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><img src=\"images/8f53295a73878494e9bc8dd6c3c7104f.jpg\" style=\"width: 25%;\" class=\"\"></p><p style=\"text-align: center; margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><br></p><p style=\"text-align: left; margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">&nbsp;<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The use of markup tags and codes remains popular today in some applications due to their ability to store complex formatting information. When the tags are made visible in the editor, however, they occupy space in the unformatted text, and as a result can disrupt the desired layout and flow.</span><br></sup></p><p style=\"text-align: left; margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bravo_(software)\" title=\"Bravo (software)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Bravo</a>, a document preparation program for the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alto_(computer)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Alto (computer)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Alto</a>&nbsp;produced at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PARC_(company)\" title=\"PARC (company)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Xerox PARC</a>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butler_Lampson\" title=\"Butler Lampson\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Butler Lampson</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Simonyi\" title=\"Charles Simonyi\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Charles Simonyi</a>&nbsp;and colleagues in 1974, is generally considered to be the first program to incorporate the WYSIWYG technology,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG#cite_note-6\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[6]</a></sup>&nbsp;displaying text with formatting (e.g. with justification, fonts, and proportional spacing of characters).<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG#cite_note-7\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">[7]</a></sup>&nbsp;The Alto monitor (72&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixels_per_inch\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pixels per inch\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">PPI</a>, based on the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(typography)\" title=\"Point (typography)\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">typographic unit</a>) was designed so that one full page of text could be seen and then printed on the first&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laser_printer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Laser printer\" style=\"color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">laser printers</a>. When the text was laid out on the screen, 72 PPI font metric files were used, but when printed, 300 PPI files were used. As a result, one would occasionally find characters and words that are slightly off—a problem that would continue up to this day.</p><p style=\"text-align: left; margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><br></p><p style=\"text-align: left; margin: 0.5em 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"><br></p>', 1);

